WEBVTT

00:13.500 --> 00:15.140
CHAPTER XXI.

00:15.540 --> 00:19.260
ELEQUENCE AND THE MASTER'S GILLED DOME.

00:19.900 --> 00:25.340
Vacation was approaching. The schoolmaster, always severe, grew severer, and more exacting

00:25.340 --> 00:31.380
than ever, for he wanted the school to make a good showing on Examination Day. His rod

00:31.380 --> 00:37.800
and his ferrel were seldom idle now, at least among the smaller pupils. Only the biggest

00:37.800 --> 00:43.360
boys and young ladies of eighteen and twenty escaped lashing. Mr. Dobbin's lashings were

00:43.360 --> 00:48.720
very vigorous ones, too, for although he carried under his wig a perfectly bald and shiny head,

00:48.780 --> 00:53.820
he had only reached middle age, and there was no sign of feebleness in his muscle. As

00:53.820 --> 00:58.780
the great day approached, all the tyranny that was in him came to the surface. He seemed

00:58.780 --> 01:04.080
to take a vindictive pleasure in punishing the least shortcomings. The consequence was

01:04.080 --> 01:08.480
that the smaller boys spent their days in terror and suffering, and their nights in

01:08.480 --> 01:14.200
plotting revenge. They threw away no opportunity to do the master a mischief, but he kept ahead

01:14.200 --> 01:19.520
all the time. The retribution that followed every vengeful success was so sweeping and

01:19.520 --> 01:26.080
that the boys all was retired from the field, badly worsted. At last they conspired together

01:26.080 --> 01:31.820
and hit upon a plan that promised a dazzling victory. They swore in the sign-painter's

01:31.820 --> 01:37.100
boy, told him the scheme, and asked his help. He had his own reason for being delighted,

01:37.400 --> 01:42.220
for the master boarded in his father's family, and had given the boy ample cause to hate

01:42.220 --> 01:47.140
him. The master's wife would go on a visit to the country in a few days, and there would

01:47.140 --> 01:52.400
be nothing to interfere with the plan. The master always prepared himself for great occasions

01:52.400 --> 01:57.980
by getting pretty well-fuddled, and the sign-painter's boy said that when the domine had reached

01:57.980 --> 02:03.520
the proper condition on examination evening, he would manage the thing, while he napped

02:03.520 --> 02:08.520
in his chair. Then he would have him awakened at the right time, and hurried away to school.

02:09.220 --> 02:15.480
In the fullness of time the interesting occasion arrived. At eight in the evening the school-house

02:15.480 --> 02:20.380
was brilliantly lighted, and adorned with wreaths and festoons of foliage and flowers.

02:21.040 --> 02:25.780
The master sat throned in his great chair upon a raised platform with his blackboard

02:25.780 --> 02:32.160
behind him. He was looking tolerably mellow. Three rows of benches on each side, and six

02:32.160 --> 02:36.880
rows in front of him, were occupied by the dignitaries of the town, and by the parents

02:36.880 --> 02:42.740
of the pupils. To his left, back of the rows of citizens, was a spacious temporary platform

02:42.740 --> 02:47.480
upon which were seated the scholars, who were to take part in the exercises of the evening.

02:48.080 --> 02:53.640
Rows of small boys, washed and dressed to an intolerable state of discomfort, rows of

02:53.640 --> 03:00.100
gawky big boys, snow-banks of girls and young ladies clad in lawn and muslim and conspicuously

03:00.100 --> 03:05.680
conscious of their bare arms, their grandmothers' ancient trinkets, their bits of pink and blue

03:05.680 --> 03:11.200
ribbon, and the flowers in their hair. All the rest of the house was filled with non-participating

03:11.200 --> 03:17.400
scholars. The exercises began. A very little boy stood up and sheepishly recited,

03:17.740 --> 03:23.480
"'You'd scarce expect one of my age to speak in public on the stage,' etc., accompanying

03:23.480 --> 03:28.380
himself with the painfully exact and spasmodic gestures which a machine might have used,

03:28.800 --> 03:34.100
supposing the machine to be a trifle out of order. But he got through safely, though cruelly

03:34.100 --> 03:39.460
scared, and got a fine round of applause when he made his manufactured bow and retired.

03:39.460 --> 03:46.300
A little shame-faced girl lisp'd. Mary had a little lamb, etc., performed a compassion-inspired

03:46.300 --> 03:52.360
curtsy, got her mead of applause, and sat down flushed and happy. Tom Sawyer stepped

03:52.360 --> 03:57.700
forward with conceited confidence, and soared into the unquenchable and indestructible

03:57.700 --> 04:03.720
"'Give me liberty or give me death!' speech, with fine fury and frantic gesticulation,

04:04.040 --> 04:09.440
and broke down in the middle of it. A ghastly stage-fright seized him, his legs quaked under

04:09.440 --> 04:14.840
him, and he was like to choke. True, he had the manifest sympathy of the house, but he

04:14.840 --> 04:20.360
had the house's silence, too, which was even worse than its sympathy. The master frowned,

04:20.680 --> 04:25.700
and this completed the disaster. Tom struggled a while, and then retired utterly defeated.

04:26.140 --> 04:28.800
There was a weak attempt at applause, but it died early.

04:29.480 --> 04:37.940
The boy stood on the burning deck, followed. Also, the Assyrian came down—and other declamatory

04:37.940 --> 04:44.380
gems. Then there were reading exercises and a spelling-fight. The meagre Latin class recited

04:44.380 --> 04:50.100
with honour—the prime feature of the evening was in order now—original compositions by

04:50.100 --> 04:55.040
the young ladies. Each in her turn stepped forward to the edge of the platform, cleared

04:55.040 --> 05:00.480
her throat, held up her manuscript tied with dainty ribbon, and proceeded to read with

05:00.480 --> 05:07.400
laboured attention to expression and punctuation. The themes were the same that had been illuminated

05:07.400 --> 05:12.700
upon similar occasions by their mothers before them, their grandmothers, and doubtless all

05:12.700 --> 05:19.260
their ancestors in the female line clear back to the crusades. Friendship was one. Memories

05:19.260 --> 05:28.200
of other days. Religion in history. Dreamland. The advantages of culture. Forms of political

05:28.200 --> 05:37.600
government compared and contrasted. Melancholy. Filial love. Heart longings, etc., etc. A

05:37.600 --> 05:42.980
prevalent feature in these compositions was a nursed and petted melancholy. Another was

05:42.980 --> 05:49.960
a wasteful and opulent gush of fine language. Another was a tendency to lug in by the ears

05:49.960 --> 05:55.620
particularly prized words and phrases until they were worn entirely out, and a peculiarity

05:55.620 --> 06:00.960
that conspicuously marked and marred them was the inveterate and intolerable sermon

06:00.960 --> 06:06.040
that wagged its crippled tail at the end of each and every one of them. No matter what

06:06.040 --> 06:10.780
the subject might be, a brain-wracking effort was made to squirm it into some aspect or

06:10.780 --> 06:16.360
other that the moral and religious mind could contemplate with edification. The glaring

06:16.360 --> 06:21.120
insincerity of these sermons was not sufficient to compass the banishment of the fashion from

06:21.120 --> 06:26.380
the schools, and it is not sufficient today. It never will be sufficient while the world

06:26.380 --> 06:31.680
stands perhaps. There is no school in all our land where the young ladies do not feel

06:31.680 --> 06:36.760
obliged to close their compositions with a sermon, and you will find that the sermon

06:36.760 --> 06:41.880
of the most frivolous and the least religious girl in the school is always the longest and

06:41.880 --> 06:47.940
the most relentlessly pious. But enough of this. Homely truth is unpalatable.

06:47.940 --> 06:54.180
Let us return to the examination. The first composition that was read was one entitled—Is

06:54.920 --> 07:01.540
this, then, life? Perhaps the reader can endure and extract from it. In the

07:01.540 --> 07:06.980
common walks of life, with what delightful emotions does the youthful mind look forward to some

07:06.980 --> 07:13.020
anticipated scene of festivity? Imagination is busy sketching rose-tinted pictures of

07:13.020 --> 07:19.700
joy. In fancy the voluptuous rotary of fashion sees herself amid the festive throng, the

07:19.700 --> 07:25.480
observed of all observers. Her graceful form, arrayed in snowy robes, is whirling through

07:25.480 --> 07:30.900
the mazes of the joyous dance. Her eye is brightest. Her step is lightest in the gay

07:30.900 --> 07:37.360
assembly. In such delicious fancies time quickly glides by, and the welcome hour arrives for

07:37.360 --> 07:43.180
her entrance into the Elysian world, of which she has had such bright dreams. How fairy-like

07:43.180 --> 07:48.620
does everything appear to her enchanted vision? Each new scene is more charming than the last,

07:49.040 --> 07:54.820
but after a while she finds that beneath this goodly exterior all is vanity. The flattery

07:54.820 --> 08:00.880
which once charmed her soul now grates harshly upon her ear. The ballroom has lost its charms,

08:01.280 --> 08:06.320
and with wasted health and embittered heart she turns away with a conviction that earthly

08:06.320 --> 08:12.120
pleasures cannot satisfy the longings of the soul, and so forth and so on. There was

08:12.120 --> 08:16.140
a buzz of gratification from time to time during the reading, accompanied by whispered

08:16.140 --> 08:22.640
ejaculations of how sweet, how eloquent, so true, etc., and after the thing had closed

08:22.640 --> 08:29.360
with a peculiarly afflicting sermon the applause was enthusiastic. Then arose a slight melancholy

08:29.360 --> 08:36.280
girl, whose face had the interesting paleness that comes of pills and indigestion, and read

08:36.280 --> 08:39.080
a poem. Two stanzas of it will do.

08:39.580 --> 08:42.640
A Missouri Maiden's Farewell to Alabama

08:43.480 --> 08:50.000
Alabama, good-bye! I love thee well, but yet for a while do I leave thee now. Sad, yes,

08:50.160 --> 08:55.840
sad thoughts of thee my heart to swell, and burning recollections throng my brow, for

08:55.840 --> 09:01.280
I have wandered through thy flowery woods, have roamed and read near Talapusa's stream,

09:01.620 --> 09:08.680
have listened to Talasea's warring floods, and wooed on Cusa's side Aurora's beam. Yet

09:08.680 --> 09:15.860
shame I not to bear an aweful heart, nor blush to turn behind my tearful eyes, tis from no

09:15.860 --> 09:23.080
stranger land I now must part, tis to no stranger's left I yield these sighs. Welcome and home

09:23.080 --> 09:29.100
were mine within this state, whose veils I leave, whose spires fade fast from me, and

09:29.100 --> 09:36.120
cold must be mine eyes, and heart and tete, when, dear Alabama, they turn cold on thee.

09:37.160 --> 09:42.920
There were very few there who knew what tete meant, but the poem was very satisfactory

09:42.920 --> 09:43.480
nevertheless.

09:44.240 --> 09:49.460
Next appeared a dark-complexion, black-eyed, black-haired young lady, who paused an impressive

09:49.460 --> 09:55.020
moment, assumed a tragic expression, and began to read in a measured, solemn tone.

09:55.680 --> 09:56.760
A vision!

09:57.900 --> 10:04.420
Dark and tempestuous was night. Around the throne on high not a single star quivered,

10:04.420 --> 10:09.780
but the deep intonations of the heavy thunder constantly vibrated upon the ear, whilst the

10:09.780 --> 10:19.440
terrific lightning reveled in angry mood through the cloudy chambers of heaven, seeming to

10:19.440 --> 10:25.140
Even the boisterous winds unanimously came forth from their mystic homes, and blustered

10:25.140 --> 10:31.740
about as if to enhance by their aid the wildness of the scene. At such a time so dark, so dreary,

10:32.060 --> 10:36.060
for human sympathy, my very spirit sighed, but instead thereof,

10:36.680 --> 10:42.820
My dearest friend, my counsellor, my comforter and guide, my joy in grief, my second bliss

10:42.820 --> 10:45.100
in joy, came to my side.

10:45.680 --> 10:51.280
She moved like one of those bright beings pictured in the sunny walks of fancies, Eden,

10:51.660 --> 10:57.480
by the romantic and young, a queen of beauty unadorned save by her own transcendent loveliness.

10:57.920 --> 11:04.140
So soft was her step, it failed to make even a sound, and but for the magical thrill imparted

11:04.140 --> 11:10.980
by her genial touch as other unobtrusive beauties, she would have glided away unperceived, unsought.

11:10.980 --> 11:16.960
A strange sadness rested upon her features, like icy tears upon the robe of December,

11:17.180 --> 11:22.400
as she pointed to the contending elements without and bad me contemplate the two beings

11:22.400 --> 11:22.980
presented.

11:24.080 --> 11:31.400
This nightmare occupied some ten pages of manuscript, and wound up with a sermon so

11:31.400 --> 11:38.500
destructive of all hope to non-Presbyterians that it took the first prize. This composition

11:38.500 --> 11:43.280
was considered to be the very finest effort of the evening. The Mayor of the village,

11:43.660 --> 11:48.580
in delivering the prize to the author of it, made a warm speech in which he said that it

11:48.580 --> 11:54.740
was by far the most eloquent thing he had ever listened to, and that Daniel Webster

11:54.740 --> 12:00.420
himself might well be proud of it. It may be remarked in passing that the number of

12:00.420 --> 12:06.000
compositions in which the word BEAUTIOUS was over-fondled, and human experience referred

12:06.000 --> 12:13.700
to as LIFE'S PAGES, was up to the usual average. Now the Master, mellow almost to the verge

12:13.700 --> 12:19.260
of geniality, put his chair aside, turned his back to the audience, and began to draw

12:19.260 --> 12:25.380
a map of America on the blackboard, to exercise the geography class upon. But he made a sad

12:25.380 --> 12:30.140
business of it, with his unsteady hand, and a smothered titter rippled over the house.

12:30.480 --> 12:35.800
He knew what the matter was, and set himself to write it. He sponged out lines and remade

12:35.800 --> 12:40.420
them, but he only distorted them more than ever, and the tittering was more pronounced.

12:40.860 --> 12:45.560
He threw his entire attention upon his work now, as if determined not to be put down by

12:45.560 --> 12:51.060
the mirth. He felt that all eyes were fastened upon him. He imagined he was succeeding, and

12:51.060 --> 12:56.560
yet the tittering continued. It even manifestly increased, and well it might. There was a

12:56.560 --> 13:01.640
garret above, pierced with a scuttle over his head, and down through this scuttle came

13:02.380 --> 13:07.560
suspended around the haunches by a string. She had a rag tied about her head and jaws

13:07.560 --> 13:12.700
to keep her from ewing. As she slowly descended she curved upward and clawed at the string.

13:13.120 --> 13:18.660
She swung downward and clawed at the intangible air. The tittering rose higher and higher.

13:18.920 --> 13:24.400
The cat was within six inches of the absorbed teacher's head, down, down, a little lower,

13:24.680 --> 13:29.460
and she grabbed his wig with her desperate claws, clung to it, and was snatched up into

13:29.460 --> 13:34.760
the garret in an instant with her trophy still in her possession. And how the light did blaze

13:34.760 --> 13:41.160
abroad from the master's bald pate, for the sign-painter's boy had gilded it! That broke

13:41.160 --> 13:45.500
up the meeting. The boys were avenged. Vacation had come.

13:46.860 --> 13:52.600
NOTE. The pretended compositions quoted in this chapter are taken without alteration

13:52.600 --> 13:59.860
from a volume entitled, PROS AND POETRY BY A WESTERN LADY. But they are exactly and precisely

13:59.860 --> 14:05.580
after the schoolgirl pattern, and hence are much happier than any mere imitations could

14:05.580 --> 14:06.080
be.

14:10.440 --> 14:18.220
CHAPTER XXII. Huck Finn quotes scriptures. Tom joined the new order of cadets of temperance,

14:18.220 --> 14:23.640
being attracted by the showy character of their regalia. He promised to abstain from

14:23.640 --> 14:29.280
smoking, chewing, and profanity, as long as he remained a member. Now he found out a new

14:29.960 --> 14:34.220
thing—namely, that to promise not to do a thing is the surest way in the world to

14:34.220 --> 14:40.000
make a body want to go and do that very thing. Tom soon found himself tormented with a desire

14:40.000 --> 14:45.020
to drink and swear. The desire grew to be so intense that nothing but the hope of a

14:45.020 --> 14:49.540
chance to display himself in his red sash kept him from withdrawing from the order.

14:50.340 --> 14:55.860
Fourth of July was coming, but he soon gave that up—gave it up before he had worn his

14:55.860 --> 15:01.100
shackles over forty-eight hours, and fixed his hopes upon old Judge Fraser, Justice of

15:01.100 --> 15:05.800
the Peace, who was apparently on his death-bed and would have a big public funeral, since

15:05.800 --> 15:11.000
he was so high and official. During three days Tom was deeply concerned about the judge's

15:11.000 --> 15:16.940
condition and hungry for news of it. Sometimes his hopes ran so high that he would venture

15:16.940 --> 15:22.240
to get out his regalia and practice before the looking-glass. But the judge had a most

15:22.240 --> 15:28.460
discouraging way of fluctuating. At last he was pronounced upon the mend, and then

15:28.460 --> 15:35.740
convalescent. Tom was disgusted, and felt a sense of injury, too. He handed in his resignation

15:35.740 --> 15:40.740
at once, and that night the judge suffered a relapse and died. Tom resolved that he would

15:40.740 --> 15:46.700
never trust a man like that again. The funeral was a fine thing—the cadets paraded in a

15:46.700 --> 15:52.600
style calculated to kill the late member with envy. Tom was a free boy again, however—there

15:52.600 --> 15:57.400
was something in that. He could drink and swear now, but found to his surprise that

15:57.400 --> 16:02.840
he did not want to. The simple fact that he could took the desire away and the charm of

16:02.840 --> 16:08.080
it. Tom presently wondered to find that his coveted vacation was beginning to hang a little

16:08.080 --> 16:13.900
heavily on his hands. He attempted a diary, but nothing happened during three days, and

16:13.900 --> 16:15.000
so he abandoned it.

16:15.220 --> 16:20.720
The first of all the negro minstrel shows came to town, and made a sensation. Tom and

16:20.720 --> 16:25.840
Joe Harper got up a band of performers and were happy for two days. Even the glorious

16:25.840 --> 16:31.540
fourth was in some sense a failure, for it rained hard, there was no procession in consequence,

16:31.820 --> 16:37.080
and the greatest man in the world, as Tom supposed, Mr. Benton, an actual United States

16:37.080 --> 16:42.840
senator, proved an overwhelming disappointment, for he was not twenty-five feet high, nor

16:42.840 --> 16:47.920
even anywhere in the neighborhood of it. A circus came, the boys played circus for three

16:47.920 --> 16:54.940
days afterward in tents made of rag-carpeting—admission, three pins for boys, two for girls, and then

16:54.940 --> 17:01.180
circusing was abandoned. A phrenologist and a mesmerizer came, and went again, and left

17:01.180 --> 17:05.740
the village duller and drearier than ever. There were some boys' and girls' parties,

17:05.740 --> 17:11.480
but they were so few and so delightful that they only made the aching voids between ache

17:11.480 --> 17:16.660
the harder. Becky Thatcher was gone to her Constantinople home to stay with her parents

17:16.660 --> 17:22.100
during vacation, so there was no bright side to life anywhere. The dreadful secret of the

17:22.100 --> 17:28.860
murder was a chronic misery. It was a very cancer for permanency and pain. Then came

17:28.860 --> 17:34.940
the measles. During two long weeks Tom lay a prisoner, dead to the world and its happenings.

17:35.260 --> 17:41.080
He was very ill. He was interested in nothing. When he got upon his feet at last and moved

17:41.080 --> 17:46.360
feebly downtown, a melancholy change had come over everything and every creature. There

17:46.360 --> 17:51.260
had been a revival, and everybody had got religion—not only the adults, but even the

17:51.260 --> 17:56.620
boys and girls. Tom went about hoping against hope for the sight of one blessed sinful face,

17:57.060 --> 18:01.580
but disappointment crossed him everywhere. He found Joe Harper studying a testament,

18:01.580 --> 18:06.920
and turned sadly away from the depressing spectacle. He sought Ben Rogers, and found

18:06.920 --> 18:12.360
him visiting the poor with a basket of tracts. He handed up Jim Hollis, who called his attention

18:12.360 --> 18:17.660
to the precious blessing of his late measles as a warning. Every boy he encountered added

18:17.660 --> 18:22.860
another ton to his depression, and when, in desperation, he flew for refuge at last to

18:22.860 --> 18:28.140
the bosom of Huckleberry Finn and was received with a scriptural quotation, his heart broke,

18:28.140 --> 18:34.980
and he crept home and to bed, realizing that he alone of all the town was lost forever and forever.

18:35.740 --> 18:40.260
And that night there came on a terrific storm, with driving rain, awful claps of thunder,

18:40.340 --> 18:44.980
and blinding sheets of lightning. He covered his head with his bedclothes and waited in a horror

18:44.980 --> 18:50.620
of suspense for his doom, for he had not the shadow of a doubt that all this hubbub was about

18:50.620 --> 18:55.880
him. He believed he had taxed the forbearance of the powers above to the extremity of endurance,

18:55.880 --> 19:01.060
and that this was the result. It might have seemed to him a waste of pomp and ammunition

19:01.060 --> 19:05.340
to kill a bug with a battery of artillery, but there seemed nothing incongruous about

19:05.340 --> 19:11.480
the getting up such an expensive thunderstorm as this to knock the turf from under an insect

19:11.480 --> 19:17.340
like himself. By and by the tempest spent itself and died without accomplishing its object.

19:17.680 --> 19:23.720
The boy's first impulse was to be grateful and reform. His second was to wait, for there might

19:23.720 --> 19:31.020
be no more storms. The next day the doctors were back. Tom had relapsed. The three weeks he spent

19:31.020 --> 19:37.020
on his back this time seemed an entire age. When he got abroad at last, he was hardly grateful

19:37.020 --> 19:42.760
that he had been spared, remembering how lonely was his estate, how companionless and forlorn he

19:42.760 --> 19:48.720
was. He drifted listlessly down the street and found Jim Hollis acting as judge in a juvenile

19:48.720 --> 19:54.960
court that was trying a cat for murder, in the presence of her victim, a bird. He found Joe

19:54.960 --> 20:01.960
Harper and Huck Finn up an alley eating a stolen melon. Poor lads! They, like Tom, had suffered a

20:01.960 --> 20:04.880
relapse. CHAPTER XXII.

20:06.600 --> 20:10.180
CHAPTER XXIII. The Salvation of Muff Potter.

20:11.140 --> 20:16.680
At last the sleepy atmosphere was stirred, and vigorously, the murder trial came on in the court.

20:16.680 --> 20:22.240
It became the absorbing topic of village talk immediately. Tom could not get away from it.

20:22.580 --> 20:27.680
Every reference to the murder sent a shudder to his heart, for his troubled conscience and fears

20:27.680 --> 20:33.460
almost persuaded him that these remarks were put forth in his hearing as feelers. He did not see

20:33.460 --> 20:38.300
how he could be suspected of knowing anything about the murder, but still he could not be

20:38.300 --> 20:43.160
comfortable in the midst of this gossip. It kept him in a cold shiver all the time.

20:43.160 --> 20:48.960
He took Huck to a lonely place to have a talk with him. It would be some relief to unseal his

20:48.960 --> 20:53.760
tongue for a little while, to divide his burden of distress with another sufferer. Moreover,

20:53.900 --> 20:57.260
he wanted to assure himself that Huck had remained discreet.

20:57.660 --> 21:01.560
Huck, have you ever told anybody about—that?

21:02.220 --> 21:03.020
About what?

21:03.660 --> 21:04.480
You know what?

21:05.120 --> 21:07.080
Oh, course I haven't.

21:07.400 --> 21:08.120
Never a word?

21:09.020 --> 21:12.220
Never a solitary word, so help me. What makes you ask?

21:12.220 --> 21:14.280
Well, I was afeard.

21:14.780 --> 21:20.280
Why, Tom Sawyer, we wouldn't be alive two days if that got found out. You know that.

21:20.640 --> 21:21.940
Tom felt more comfortable.

21:22.580 --> 21:23.420
After a pause.

21:23.980 --> 21:27.540
Huck, they couldn't anybody get you to tell, could they?

21:28.460 --> 21:32.900
Get me to tell? Why, if I wanted that half-breed devil to drown me,

21:32.900 --> 21:35.700
they could get me to tell. They ain't no different way.

21:36.480 --> 21:40.260
Well, that's all right, then. I reckon we're safe as long as we keep Mum.

21:40.260 --> 21:42.880
But let's swear again, anyway. It's more sure.

21:43.460 --> 21:44.280
I'm agreed.

21:44.740 --> 21:47.060
So they swore again, with dread solemnities.

21:47.460 --> 21:50.720
What is the talk around, Huck? I've heard a power of it.

21:51.020 --> 21:55.060
Talk? Well, it's just Muff Potter, Muff Potter, Muff Potter all the time.

21:55.200 --> 21:59.180
It keeps me in a sweat, constant, so as I want to hide somewheres.

21:59.440 --> 22:03.500
That's just the same way they go on round me. I reckon he's a goner.

22:03.640 --> 22:05.360
Don't you feel sorry for him sometimes?

22:06.040 --> 22:09.440
Most always, most always. He ain't no account. But

22:09.440 --> 22:13.380
then he ain't ever done anything to hurt anybody. Just fishes a little,

22:13.600 --> 22:17.040
to get money to get drunk on, and loess around considerable.

22:17.640 --> 22:22.440
But, Lord, we all do that. Least ways most of us. Preachers and such like.

22:23.020 --> 22:27.320
But he's kind of good. He give me half a fish once, when there weren't

22:27.320 --> 22:31.880
enough for two. And lots of times he's kind of stood by me when I was

22:31.880 --> 22:36.260
out of luck. Well, he's mended kites for me, Huck, and knitted hooks

22:36.260 --> 22:39.080
onto my line. I wish we could get him out of there.

22:39.540 --> 22:44.320
My, we couldn't get him out, Tom. And besides, to do any good, they'd

22:44.320 --> 22:45.020
catch him again.

22:45.240 --> 22:49.420
Yes, so they would. But I hate to hear him abuse him so like the

22:49.420 --> 22:51.840
Dickens, when he never done that.

22:52.560 --> 22:56.620
I do too, Tom. Lord, I hear him say he's the bloodiest-looking villain

22:56.620 --> 23:00.900
in this country, and they wonder he wasn't ever hung before. Yes, they

23:00.900 --> 23:05.100
talk like that all the time. I've heard him say that if he was to get

23:05.100 --> 23:07.920
free they'd lynch him. And they do it too.

23:08.460 --> 23:12.020
The boys had a long talk, but it brought them little comfort. As the

23:12.020 --> 23:14.700
twilight drew on, they found themselves hanging about the neighborhood

23:14.700 --> 23:18.660
of the little isolated jail, perhaps with an undefined hope that

23:18.660 --> 23:22.080
something would happen that might clear away their difficulties. But

23:22.080 --> 23:25.820
nothing happened. There seemed to be no angels or fairies interested in

23:25.820 --> 23:27.140
this luckless captive.

23:27.820 --> 23:31.580
The boys did as they had often done before. Went to the cell grating

23:31.580 --> 23:35.460
and gave Potter some tobacco and matches. He was on the ground floor,

23:35.500 --> 23:39.400
and there were no guards. His gratitude for their gifts had always

23:39.400 --> 23:43.680
smote their conscience before. It cut deeper than ever this time. They

23:43.680 --> 23:46.780
felt cowardly and treacherous to the last degree when Potter said,

23:47.020 --> 23:51.060
You've been mighty good to me, boys. Better than anybody else in this

23:51.060 --> 23:55.940
town. And I don't forget it. I don't. Often I says to myself, says I,

23:56.100 --> 23:59.560
I used to mend all the boys' kites and things, and show them where the

23:59.560 --> 24:03.740
good fishing places was, and befriend them when I could. And now

24:03.740 --> 24:07.520
they've all forgot old Muff when he's in trouble. But Tom don't and

24:07.520 --> 24:11.600
Huck don't. They don't forget him, says I, and I don't forget them.

24:12.060 --> 24:16.020
Well, boys, I had done an awful thing. Drunk and crazy at the time.

24:16.340 --> 24:19.880
That's the only way I count for it. And now I got the swing for it,

24:19.880 --> 24:24.680
and it's right. Right and best, too, I reckon. I hope so, anyway.

24:25.360 --> 24:28.980
Well, we won't talk about that. I don't want to make you feel bad.

24:28.980 --> 24:33.740
You've befriended me. But what I want to say is, don't you ever get

24:33.740 --> 24:38.420
drunk. Then you won't ever get here. Stand a little further west. So

24:38.420 --> 24:42.280
that's it. It's a prime comfort to see faces that's friendly when a

24:42.280 --> 24:46.180
body's in such a muck of trouble. And there don't none come here but

24:46.180 --> 24:52.640
yorn. Good friendly faces. Good friendly faces. Get up on one other's

24:52.640 --> 24:57.340
backs, and let me touch them. That's it. Shake hands. Yorn'll come

24:57.340 --> 25:02.600
through the bars, but mine's too big. Little hands and weak. And they've

25:02.600 --> 25:06.440
helped Muff Potter a power, and they'd help him more if they could.

25:07.180 --> 25:10.600
Tom went home miserable, and his dreams that night were full of

25:10.600 --> 25:13.980
horrors. The next day and the day after he hung about the courtroom,

25:14.520 --> 25:18.520
drawn by an impossibly resistible impulse to go in but forcing himself

25:18.520 --> 25:22.540
to stay out. Huck was having the same experience. They studiously

25:22.540 --> 25:27.040
avoided each other. Each wandered away from time to time, but the same

25:27.040 --> 25:31.000
dismal fascination always brought them back presently. Tom kept his

25:31.000 --> 25:34.880
ears open when idlers sauntered out of the courtroom, but invariably

25:34.880 --> 25:38.860
heard distressing news. The toils were closing more and more

25:38.860 --> 25:43.280
relentlessly around poor Potter. At the end of the second day the

25:43.280 --> 25:46.880
village talk was to the effect that Injun Joe's evidence stood firm and

25:46.880 --> 25:50.400
unshaken, and that there was not the slightest question as to what the

25:50.400 --> 25:54.720
jury's verdict would be. Tom was out late that night, and came to bed

25:54.720 --> 25:58.740
through the window. He was in a tremendous state of excitement. It was

25:58.740 --> 26:02.480
hours before he got to sleep. All the village flocked to the courthouse

26:02.480 --> 26:07.120
the next morning, for this was to be the great day. Both sexes were about

26:07.120 --> 26:11.060
equally represented in the packed audience. After a long wait the jury

26:11.060 --> 26:15.840
filed in and took their places. Shortly afterward, Potter, pale and

26:15.840 --> 26:20.340
haggard, timid and hopeless, was brought in with chains upon him, and

26:20.340 --> 26:24.080
seated where all the curious eyes could stare at him. No less

26:24.080 --> 26:28.340
conspicuous was Injun Joe, stolid as ever. There was another pause,

26:28.580 --> 26:31.480
and then the judge arrived and the sheriff proclaimed the opening of

26:31.480 --> 26:35.300
the court. The usual whisperings among the lawyers and gathering

26:35.300 --> 26:39.300
together of papers followed. These details and accompanying delays

26:39.300 --> 26:43.320
worked up an atmosphere of preparation that was as impressive as it was

26:43.320 --> 26:47.880
fascinating. Now a witness was called who testified that he found Muff

26:47.880 --> 26:51.260
Potter washing in the brook at an early hour of the morning that the

26:51.260 --> 26:55.560
murder was discovered, and that he immediately sneaked away. After some

26:55.560 --> 26:58.120
further questioning, counsel for the prosecution said,

26:58.540 --> 27:02.680
"'Take the witness.' The prisoner raised his eyes for a moment, but

27:02.680 --> 27:05.000
dropped them again when his own counsel said,

27:05.420 --> 27:09.400
"'I have no questions to ask him.' The next witness proved the finding

27:09.400 --> 27:13.000
of the knife near the corpse. Counsel for the prosecution said,

27:13.280 --> 27:14.620
"'Take the witness.'

27:14.620 --> 27:18.680
"'I have no questions to ask him,' Potter's lawyer replied. A third

27:18.680 --> 27:21.940
witness swore he had often seen the knife in Potter's possession.

27:22.800 --> 27:26.840
"'Take the witness.' Counsel for Potter declined to question him.

27:27.320 --> 27:31.020
The faces of the audience began to betray annoyance. Did this attorney

27:31.020 --> 27:34.700
mean to throw away his client's life without an effort? Several

27:34.700 --> 27:38.260
witnesses deposed concerning Potter's guilty behavior when brought to

27:38.260 --> 27:41.580
the scene of the murder. They were allowed to leave the stand without

27:41.580 --> 27:45.880
being cross-questioned. Every detail of the damaging circumstances

27:45.880 --> 27:49.000
that occurred in the graveyard upon that morning, which all present

27:49.000 --> 27:53.160
remembered so well, was brought out by credible witnesses, but none of

27:53.160 --> 27:57.060
them were cross-examined by Potter's lawyer. The perplexity and

27:57.060 --> 28:00.820
dissatisfaction of the house expressed itself in murmurs and provoked a

28:00.820 --> 28:04.160
reproof from the bench. Counsel for the prosecution now said,

28:04.580 --> 28:09.240
"'By the oaths of citizens whose simple word is above suspicion, we

28:09.240 --> 28:13.300
have fastened this awful crime, beyond all possibility of question,

28:13.300 --> 28:19.780
upon the unhappy prisoner at the bar. We rest our case here.' A groan

28:19.780 --> 28:23.740
escaped from poor Potter, and he put his face in his hands and rocked

28:23.740 --> 28:27.660
his body softly to and fro, while a painful silence reigned in the

28:27.660 --> 28:33.000
courtroom. Many men were removed, and many women's compassion testified

28:33.000 --> 28:38.000
itself in tears. Counsel for the defense rose and said, "'Your honor,

28:38.320 --> 28:42.540
in our remarks at the opening of this trial we foreshadowed our purpose

28:42.540 --> 28:46.080
to prove that our client did this fearful deed while under the

28:46.080 --> 28:51.040
influence of a blind and irresponsible delirium produced by drink. We

28:51.040 --> 28:55.400
have changed our mind. We shall not offer that plea.' Then to the

28:55.400 --> 29:01.600
clerk, "'Call Thomas Sawyer.' A puzzled amazement awoke in every face

29:01.600 --> 29:06.420
in the house, not even accepting Potter's. Every eye fastened itself

29:06.420 --> 29:10.980
with wondering interest upon Tom as he rose and took his place upon the

29:10.980 --> 29:15.600
stand. The boy looked wild enough, for he was badly scared. The oath

29:15.600 --> 29:20.660
was administered. Thomas Sawyer, where were you on the seventeenth of

29:20.660 --> 29:26.060
June, about the hour of midnight?' Tom glanced at Injun Joe's iron face,

29:26.320 --> 29:30.600
and his tongue failed him. The audience listened breathless, but the

29:30.600 --> 29:34.620
words refused to come. After a few moments, however, the boy got a little

29:34.620 --> 29:38.240
of his strength back, and managed to put enough of it into his voice to

29:38.240 --> 29:39.920
make part of the house hear.

29:40.500 --> 29:41.920
"'In the graveyard?'

29:42.640 --> 29:46.300
"'A little bit louder, please. Don't be afraid. You were in the

29:46.300 --> 29:50.840
graveyard.' A contemptuous smile flitted across Injun Joe's face.

29:51.040 --> 29:54.630
"'Were you anywhere near Horse William's grave?'

29:55.160 --> 29:56.240
"'Yes, sir.'

29:56.240 --> 29:59.230
"'Speak up, just a trifle louder. How near were you?'

29:59.660 --> 30:01.390
"'Near as I am to you.'

30:01.660 --> 30:03.390
"'Were you hidden or not?'

30:03.760 --> 30:04.860
"'I was hid.'

30:04.860 --> 30:06.040
"'Where?'

30:06.040 --> 30:08.960
"'Behind the elms that's on the edge of the grave.'

30:08.960 --> 30:11.740
Injun Joe gave a barely perceptible start.

30:12.300 --> 30:13.420
"'Anyone with you?'

30:13.780 --> 30:16.000
"'Yes, sir. I went there with—'

30:16.160 --> 30:20.060
"'Wait. Wait a moment. Never mind mentioning your companion's name.

30:20.180 --> 30:24.080
We will produce him at the proper time. Did you carry anything there

30:24.080 --> 30:27.080
with you?' Tom hesitated and looked confused.

30:27.280 --> 30:31.100
"'Speak out, my boy. Don't be diffident. The truth is always

30:31.100 --> 30:33.460
respectable. What did you take there?'

30:36.940 --> 30:37.860
"'Only—uh—uh—dead cat.'

30:37.860 --> 30:40.580
There was a ripple of mirth which the court checked.

30:40.940 --> 30:45.140
"'We will produce the skeleton of that cat. Now, my boy, tell us

30:45.140 --> 30:48.320
everything that occurred. Tell it in your own way. Don't skip

30:48.320 --> 30:49.880
anything, and don't be afraid.'

30:50.820 --> 30:55.120
Tom began hesitatingly at first, but as he warmed to his subject his

30:55.120 --> 30:59.000
words flowed more and more easily. In a little while every sound

30:59.000 --> 31:04.100
ceased but his own voice. Every eye fixed itself upon him. With

31:04.100 --> 31:07.420
parted lips and bated breath the audience hung upon his words,

31:07.700 --> 31:11.260
taking no note of time, wrapped in the ghastly fascination of the

31:11.260 --> 31:16.380
tale. The strain upon pent emotion reached its climax when the boys

31:16.380 --> 31:21.300
said, "'And as the doctor fetched the board around and Muff Potter

31:21.300 --> 31:23.960
fell, Injun Joe jumped with a knife and—'

31:24.720 --> 31:28.660
Crash! Quick as lightning the half-breed sprang for a window,

31:28.660 --> 31:31.780
tore his way through all opposers, and was gone.'

31:32.920 --> 31:35.100
End of chapter 23

